            "id": "1d04d4293f2b4f2c99c99",
            "questionText": "An athlete with a mass of $!$75\\,\\text{kg}$!$ performs a box jump. From the moment they push off the ground, they reach a peak height of $!$0.6\\,\\text{m}$!$ in $!$0.4\\,\\text{s}$!$. Assuming that the work done against gravity is the primary useful energy transfer, and taking the acceleration due to gravity as $!$9.8\\,\\text{m/s}^2$!$, calculate the average power (in watts) generated by the athlete during the ascent phase of the jump.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "df235d4ee3ac405883726",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the correct formula for calculating the change in gravitational potential energy. Which of the following formulas represents the change in gravitational potential energy ($!$\\Delta E_p$!$) in terms of mass ($!$m$!$), gravitational acceleration ($!$g$!$), and change in height ($!$\\Delta h$!$)?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "8af41638-67d0-4304-afe4-278a3e5c24b8"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta E_p = m \\cdot g \\cdot \\Delta h$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta E_p = m + g + \\Delta h$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta E_p = \\frac{1}{2} m \\cdot v^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "07b0d0684c594301afa6b",
                    "stepText": "Great! Now, using the formula from the previous step, calculate the gravitational potential energy change by substituting the values: mass = $!$75\\,\\text{kg}$!$, gravitational acceleration = $!$9.8\\,\\text{m/s}^2$!$, and height change = $!$0.6\\,\\text{m}$!$. What is the energy in Joules?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "441"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "J",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "8af41638-67d0-4304-afe4-278a3e5c24b8"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "ef53c256f14045299c4a0",
                    "stepText": "Now that we have the energy value, let's select the correct formula for calculating average power. Which of the following formulas correctly relates power ($!$P$!$), energy change ($!$\\Delta E$!$), and time ($!$t$!$)?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "f093a546-8db4-44fa-9763-df65c6e6db0e"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$P = \\frac{\\Delta E}{t}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$P = \\Delta E \\cdot t$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$P = \\frac{t}{\\Delta E}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "bb25b77614a54b07bfedc",
                    "stepText": "Finally, using the energy value computed earlier and the time duration of $!$0.4\\,\\text{s}$!$, calculate the average power generated by the athlete during the ascent phase. What is the power in Watts?",
